contentrichtext.text: In [[Roman mythology]], '''Nascio''' ([[Latin]]: "birth") was one of many [[goddess]]es of [[childbirth|birth]], and a protector of [[infants]]. She assisted [[Lucina (goddess)|Lucina]] in her functions, and was analogous to the Greek [[Eileithyia]]. She had a sanctuary in the neighborhood of [[Ardea (RM)|Ardea]].<ref>[[Cicero]], ''[[De Natura Deorum|On the Nature of Gods]]'', 3. 18</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mythindex.com/roman-mythology/N/Nascio.html|title=Nascio|publisher=Roman Myth Index|accessdate=2008-06-10}}</ref> ==See also== * [[List of Roman birth and childhood deities]] * ''[[Di nixi]]'' ==References== {{Reflist}} [[Category:Roman mythology]] [[Category:Roman goddesses]] [[Category:Childhood goddesses]] {{Ancient-Rome-myth-stub}}
